@node "require" "Requirements "
@next "install"
@prev "legal"

@{i}Requirements @{ui}

Any PAL Amiga with OS 1.3 or higher (with 2MB Chip if you want to hear the
music and SFX).  A minimum of 1.5MB Chip is required.

A hard drive is strongly recommended to speed things up (like when loading
the music and SFX).

It was written using AMOS Professional 2 on my A1200 with 10MB, CD-ROM,
1.1gig hard drive, and of course it runs perfectly!

It has also been tested on:
   A500+ with 2MB
   A1200 with 2MB
@endnode


@node "install" "Installation "
@next "playing"
@prev "require"

@{i}Installation @{ui}

  To install the game to a hard drive, just copy the contents of the disks
  to a new drawer (any name will do, just as long as you can remember
  what's in the drawer!). The drawer should therefore contain the drawers
  "NPQ," "NPQ2," "NPQ3" and "NPQ4." If you received Now That's What I Call
  A Pop Quiz in archive format & you want to copy the game onto disk, then
  simply copy the contents of the drawer, "NPQ", onto a blank disk and
  name the disk "NPQ." Repeat the process for drawers "NPQ2," "NPQ3" and
  "NPQ4." Don't forget to put a bootblock on NPQ or disk 1. Once
  everything is done, reset your computer and place "NPQ" or disk 1 in
  df0: if your playing from disk or once you've installed the game on
  your hard drive, move the Now_Pop_Quiz_HD+CD icon out of the NPQ drawer
  and put it into the parent drawer (whatever you named it, possibly
  Now_Pop_Quiz). Now double click on the Now_Pop_Quiz_HD+CD icon and all
  assigns are done automatically everytime you play the game.  Click on
  this icon if you're playing from a CD as well.

  Please note, if you copied the NPQ/NPQ2/NPQ3/NPQ4 drawers to disk,
  remember to not leave a drawer called NPQ or NPQ2 or NPQ3 or NPQ4 on
  their respective disks, i.e. don't have a pathname like:
  NPQ:NPQ/ or NPQ2:NPQ2/ or NPQ3:NPQ3/ or NPQ4:NPQ4/ !!!!!

  Please also note, for hard disk users, that 'amos.library' and
  'diskfont.library' should be in your 'libs' directory on the system
  partition of your hard disk.  If they are not present then copy them
  straight over from the 'libs' directory on NPQ (disk 1).

@endnode


@node "playing" "Playing the game      "
@next "credits"
@prev "install"

@{i}Playing the game @{ui}

The game consists of 5 rounds in which you must correctly answer as many
questions as possible.  At the beginning of each round you will have the
option of choosing from 4 subjects based on pop music (ranging from 'the
Fabulous Fifties' to 'the Best Album in the World Ever' to 'Indie Scene').
The next 3 questions will be based on that topic of music.  Sometimes (but
only if you're lucky) you will receive a 4th question.

Before a question is displayed on the screen, occasionaly you may get a
BONUS question.  This will be indicated by a vertically placed piece of
text to the left of the screen which (strangely) will read 'BONUS QUESTION.'
You will be rewarded a BONUS disc only if you correctly answer a BONUS
question.  This will mean that when you get to the TOP TEN game an
incorrect answer will still move you up the TOP TEN ladder (more details to
follow). A maximum of 8 bonus discs per game may be awarded.

Each correct answer to the questions in the 5 rounds (which are
multiple choice) awards you with 1 second towards the TOP TEN game, which
is the final game.  The seconds you have collated throughout the 5 rounds
in the main game represent how long you have to answer as many questions as
possible on a particular subject.  There are many different subjects in the
game's question bank, but the computer will only provide you with the option
to choose one of 2.  On correctly answering these questions you will move
up the TOP TEN ladder.  An incorrect answer will move you down (unless you
have a bonus disc available which will still move you up automatically).

More points are awarded as you climb the TOP TEN ladder.  Once your time is
up, your points will be calculated based on how many questions you answered
correctly (in the 1st 5 rounds), the time you took to answer them, the
number you reached on the TOP TEN ladder, and any bonus game points which
you may have been awarded (more details to follow).

If your score is amongst the 10 highest then you will be taken to the
hi-score table* where will be asked to enter your name.

The game will then return to the options screen, where you have the
opportunity to have another game or (I know you wouldn't want to) quit.

The Bonus game is fairly simple and should not be confused with Bonus
questions. At the end of round 1, you will be presented with a screen
whereby you have to stop the black piece on the screen by pressing the fire
button and then a segment of a picture will be revealed. After providing you
with an opportunity to try and figure out who the picture is of, you will
move onto another screen where you can select your answer from a multiple
choice of 50 options. If you guess correct after round 1, your bonus will be
worth 1000 points (which is added to your score at the end of the game). An
incorrect answer means you get to remove another segment of the picture after
round 2. A correct answer at this stage and the bonus will be worth 800.
After round 3, 600, round 4, 400 and round 5, 200. If you don't correctly
answer the bonus game question after round 5 (even though by this time the
entire picture will be displayed) then you score a Bonus game bonus of 0!

Hope that's all clear!?!

The best way of playing the game is to play it again and again so that you
know what is expected of you!


